results.notes:
This is a new mushroom that sprung up this week on our lawn. Even though this appears on our lawn, I think it has to do with the composted horse manure that covers our front lawn. Last summer, we applied a thick layer of composted horse manure from local suppliers and I’ve been fascinated by all the different fungi and other things popping up. This is one I haven’t been able to identify. Here are the details (see photos):

We’ve had an abundance of rain this winter. The past two days have had gentle rain and the daytime temperatives are in the high 50s low 60s, with overnight temps in the low to mid 40s F. These are growing in a diffuse sun to afternoon sunny spot about 10 ft from two liquid amber trees.

Strong pungent musty mushroom smell, fragrant of earth. Stays on my fingers after handling them.

Mature size seems to be about 3-4 inches across. Stems long 2-3inches long and narrow. Stems are cream to brownish. Darker than the cap.

White to cream colored cap is roundish shape. Looks like something was nibbling on the caps. The morning dew made the cap feel slightly slippery but when dry feels soft and smooth.

Gills are whiteish in younger specimens turning a greyish brown as it matures. This veil when young. See photos.

Prolific spores are brownish, like fine cocoa powder.

Stem is long and flexible, and in the older specimens turns slightly brownish and has an almost candy like sheen to them.

Thallus yellow, of dispersed small convex areoles. Apothecia common, lecanorine, thalline margin reduced but persistent, bright yellow, disk yellow but slightly olivaceous at close up view. Paraphyses simple, cylindrical, rarely with slightly swollen caps. Asci broadly clavate.

Spores 8/ascus, simple, hyaline, ellipsoid, 15.0×5.9 (n=3).

I struggled with this one and am guessing it is a normally saxicolous species like C. rosulans or possibly C. aurella.
